fields.description:
When using the following S3 IAM policy:
{code}
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Stmt1361565586161",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::*"
    }
  ]
}
{code}

Non-eucalyptus account users are able to do the following:

* create buckets
* delete buckets
* upload objects
* delete objects
* set ACLs in buckets
{code}
 ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-account1-user02 setacl --acl-grant read:190858417056 s3://sometest
s3://sometest/: ACL updated
$ ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-account1-user02 info s3://sometest
s3://sometest/ (bucket):
   Location:  us-east-1
   policy: none
   ACL:       account1: FULL_CONTROL
   ACL:       account6: READ
{code}

They aren't able to do the following:

* set ACLs on objects as they are being uploaded (hangs)
{code}
./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-account1-user02 --acl-public --guess-mime-type put test2.txt s3://sometest/test2.txt
{code}
* get objects (get Forbidden error)
{code}
$ ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-account1-user02 get s3://sometest/test.sh test-user02.sh
s3://sometest/test.sh -> test-user02.sh  [1 of 1]
ERROR: S3 error: 403 (Forbidden):
{code}

*Workaround*

If the S3 IAM policy is as follows:
{code}
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Stmt1361565586161",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::*",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::*/*"
    }
  ]
}
{code}

Everything works as expected.

comments.body:
Hey [~mmunn1],

Yes, you are correct, the bucket and object are looked at as separate, but the issue comes with the wildcard - which looking [at the documentation for IAM explains how the wildcard is evaulated|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/Using_Identifiers.html#Identifiers_ARNs].  For example, if you look at the following test policy by AWS:

{code}
{
   "Statement":[
      {
         "Effect":"Allow",
         "Action":[
            "s3:ListAllMyBuckets"
         ],
         "Resource":"arn:aws:s3:::*"
      }
       ]
}
{code}

This allows a user to list all objects for all buckets under that account.  

I tested the following policy on AWS S3:

{code}
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Stmt1361565586161",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::*"
    }
  ]
}
{code}

I was able to do all actions associated with buckets and objects.  The two actions where Eucalyptus errors out - 

* setting an ACL on an object
* download an object using GET

worked on AWS S3.  The results of my tests are below:

{code}
$ iam-userlistpolicies -u hasp -v
s3-all
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Stmt1361565586161",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::*"
    }
  ]
}

IsTruncated: false
$ ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-hasp mb s3://test-s3-wildcard
Bucket 's3://test-s3-wildcard/' created
$ ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-hasp ls s3://test-s3-wildcard
2013-09-18 19:50      4935   s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py
$ ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-hasp del s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py
File s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py deleted
 ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-hasp --acl-public --guess-mime-type put stub_ldifs.py s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py
stub_ldifs.py -> s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py  [1 of 1]
 4935 of 4935   100% in    0s     5.49 kB/s  done
Public URL of the object is: http://test-s3-wildcard.s3.amazonaws.com/stub_ldifs.py
$ ./s3cmd/s3cmd --config=.s3cfg-hasp get s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py stub_ldifs.py.test
s3://test-s3-wildcard/stub_ldifs.py -> stub_ldifs.py.test  [1 of 1]
 4935 of 4935   100% in    0s     9.58 kB/s  done
{code}

I am reopening this because I figured this helps explain the issue better.  Hope this helps.  Please let me know if there are any questions.

[~sjones]
The proposed "fix" is the same as the following which is the policy generated for  "Amazon S3 Full Access"  this allows only s3 actions on all resources. The problem is that
there are other compatibility issues with Bucket/Object, wildcard combinations. There are also differences in the Bucket/Object action mappings see the bug description for this issue.

{code}
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Resource": "*",
    }
  ]
}
{code}

1) The arn "arn:aws:s3:::*/readme.txt" does work on AWS.

[~zhill],[~sjones] If I apply the AWS "Amazon S3 Full Access" policy below to Euca without this fix it puts a "*" into the db table auth_auth.auth_auth_type instead of s3:bucket or s3:object? Is this another bug? My fix is creating the same auth_type in the database as the policy below?
{code}
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Resource": "*",
    }
  ]
}
{code}
